 future. As Osborne explains, the engineering breakthroughs that made modernist churches feasible themselves raised questions that were, for many Catholics, fundamentally theological. Couldn’t technological improvements engender worship spaces that better reflected God's presence in the contemporary world? Detailing the social, architectural, and theological movements that made modern churches possible, American Catholics and the Churches of Tomorrow breaks important new ground in the history of American Catholicism, and also presents new lines of thought for scholars attracted to modern architectural and urban history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCatholic church buildingszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCatholic church buildings-United States-History-20th century. 0aElectronic books. 0aModern movement (Architecture)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModern movement (Architecture)-United States-History-20th century. 0aModernism (Christian theology)xCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Christian theology)xCatholic ChurchxHistoryy20thcentury. 0aModernism (Christian theology)-Catholic Church-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Catholicism.  aCatholic Church.  aChurch Architecture.  aEcclesiology.  aEschatology.  aLiturgical Studies.  aModern Architecture.  aReligion and Science.  aSecond Vatican Council.  aVatican II.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226561165423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226561165/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles